frameDefinitions: An Experiencer is involved in a bodily injury to a Body_part.
An Agent acts to  cause a Experiencer to feel a certain emotion.
An Entity is undergoing a change in age typically associated with some deterioration or change in state.
In this frame a Deformer deforms a Patient possibly against a Resistant_surface such that it undergoes a shape-change from its canonical or original shape into the Configuration, a new shape.
Some phenomenon (the Stimulus) provokes a particular emotion in an Experiencer.
The words in this frame describe situations in which an Agent or a Cause injures a Victim.
frameExamples: I think that I <t>hurt</t> myself pretty bad back there.
I was so <t>offended</t> by her behaviour towards me.
Ellen <t>crumpled</t> the paper into a ball.
Nightmare on Elm Street <t>scared</t> me silly.
Rod saw his father <t>beating</t> his mother.
listRoleDefinitions: The location on the body of the <fen>Experiencer</fen> where the bodily injury takes place.
The being or entity that is injured.
The time when the harming event occurs.
The place where the harming event occurs.
The <fen>Agent</fen> is the person who's action's cause an emotion in the <fen>Experiencer</fen>.
The Experiencer feels an emotion as caused by the <fen>Agent</fen>.
The <fen>Event</fen> is the occasion or happening that evokes emotions in the <fen>Experiencer</fen>. This <fen>Event</fen> occurs as the direct result of a sentient being's actions.
When the Agent causes emotion in the Experiencer.
The location where the <fen>Agent</fen> causes the <fen>Experiencer</fen> to feel the emotion.
The <fen>Entity</fen> which is undergoing aging.
The <fen>Time</fen> during which the <fen>Entity</fen> ages.
This role indicates where the <fen>Entity</fen> is located.
The <fen>Deformer</fen> is the one who does the reshaping.
The <fen>Patient</fen> is the entity acted on and that undergoes a change.
The <fen>Cause</fen> is an animate or inanimate entity, a force, or event that produces an effect. Volitionality is not a necessary characteristic of <fen>Cause</fen>s.
A state that holds of the <fen>Patient</fen> or a relation that holds among the constituent parts of the <fen>Patient</fen> as a result of the arranging action.
The role <fen>Time</fen> identifies when the <fen>Deformer</fen> intentionally affects the <fen>Patient</fen>.
The <fen>Place</fen> indicates where the <fen>Deformer</fen> intentionally affects the <fen>Patient</fen>.
The <fen>Experiencer</fen> reacts emotionally or psychologically to the <fen>Stimulus</fen>.
The <fen>Stimulus</fen> is the event or entity which brings about the emotional or psychological state of the <fen>Experiencer</fen>.
The <fen>Time</fen> when the <fen>Experiencer</fen> has an emotion as caused by the <fen>Stimulus</fen>.
<fen>Agent</fen> is the person causing the <fen>Victim</fen>'s injury.

The <fen>Victim</fen> is the being or entity that is injured.  If the <fen>Victim</fen> is included in the phrase indicating <fen>Body_part</fen>, the <fen>Victim</fen> role is tagged on a second role layer (see 3rd example).
The <fen>Body_part</fen> identifies the location on the body where the bodily injury takes place.
The <fen>Cause</fen> marks expressions that indicate some non-intentional, typically non-human, force that inflicts harm on the <fen>Victim</fen>
<fen>Time</fen> identifies the time when the harm-causing event occurs.
<fen>Place</fen> identifies the place where the harm causing event occurs.
